════════════════════════════════════════
STEP 1 — PARSE AND INVENTORY
════════════════════════════════════════
Read every ticket. For each one, extract:

  ticket_id: [PROJ-XXX]
  title: [original title]
  type: bug | feature | chore | refactor | spike | unknown
  description_quality: clear | vague | contradictory | incomplete
  has_acceptance_criteria: yes | no | partial
  mentions_specific_files_or_code: yes | no
  estimated_complexity: trivial | small | medium | large | unknown
  raw_summary: [1–2 sentences — what is this ticket actually asking for, 
                in plain engineering terms, ignoring business language]

Output this as a table first so it is easy to scan.

════════════════════════════════════════
STEP 2 — DETECT PROBLEMS
════════════════════════════════════════
Before normalizing anything, identify issues in the ticket set.
Check for each of the following and flag every instance found:

── DUPLICATES ──
Are any two tickets asking for the same thing or overlapping substantially?
  flag: DUPLICATE
  tickets: [PROJ-XXX, PROJ-YYY]
  overlap: [what they share]
  recommendation: MERGE | KEEP_BOTH_SEPARATE | CLARIFY

── HIDDEN DEPENDENCIES ──
Does any ticket implicitly require another ticket to be done first, even if
no dependency is stated in Jira?
  flag: HIDDEN_DEPENDENCY
  ticket: [PROJ-XXX]
  depends_on: [PROJ-YYY]
  reason: [why — be specific about what PROJ-XXX assumes PROJ-YYY has done]

── CONFLICTS ──
Do any two tickets ask for things that contradict each other?
  flag: CONFLICT
  tickets: [PROJ-XXX, PROJ-YYY]
  conflict: [what they disagree on]
  recommendation: [which to follow, or what clarification is needed]

── SCOPE ISSUES ──
Does any ticket ask for something that is clearly out of scope for a coding
agent working on a single repository? (e.g. infrastructure changes, design
decisions, third-party procurement, legal review)
  flag: OUT_OF_SCOPE
  ticket: [PROJ-XXX]
  reason: [why this cannot be implemented in code alone]
  recommendation: SKIP | PARTIAL_IMPLEMENTATION | BLOCK_ON_HUMAN

── BUNDLE TICKETS ──
Does any single ticket actually contain multiple independent tasks bundled
together? (signal: "and also", multiple unrelated acceptance criteria, 
title with "/" or "&")
  flag: BUNDLE
  ticket: [PROJ-XXX]
  sub_tasks: [list the distinct tasks hidden inside]
  recommendation: SPLIT into [N] separate tasks

── VAGUE REQUIREMENTS ──
Does any ticket use business language that cannot be directly mapped to code
without making assumptions?
  flag: VAGUE
  ticket: [PROJ-XXX]
  vague_phrase: [the exact phrase that is unclear]
  interpretation_needed: [what engineering decision this forces]
  my_interpretation: [how you will interpret it — be explicit]
  confidence: high | medium | low

If confidence is low: flag as NEEDS_HUMAN_CLARIFICATION and do not include
this ticket in the final task list. Output it separately.

── MISSING CONTEXT ──
Does any ticket reference something that doesn't have enough detail to implement?
(e.g. "update the existing flow" — which flow? "fix the performance issue" — which one?)
  flag: MISSING_CONTEXT
  ticket: [PROJ-XXX]
  missing: [what information is absent]
  blocking: yes | no (is this a blocker or can you make a reasonable assumption?)

════════════════════════════════════════
STEP 3 — NORMALIZE INTO ENGINEERING TASKS
════════════════════════════════════════
After resolving the problems in Step 2, produce a clean normalized task list.

Rules:
- One entry per distinct engineering task (split bundles, merge duplicates)
- Translate all business language into engineering language
- Each task must be implementable without human clarification
- Tasks flagged as NEEDS_HUMAN_CLARIFICATION are excluded from this list
  and go into the BLOCKED section at the end
- Preserve the original ticket ID(s) as reference

For each normalized task:

  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  TASK ID: [T-001, T-002, ...] (your numbering, not Jira's)
  SOURCE TICKETS: [PROJ-XXX] or [PROJ-XXX + PROJ-YYY merged]
  TITLE: [clear, verb-first engineering title]
  TYPE: feature | bugfix | refactor | chore
  
  WHAT:
  [Precise description of what needs to be built or changed.
   No business language. No ambiguity.
   If you made an interpretation, state it clearly:
   "Interpreted 'user dashboard' as a new /dashboard route that 
   displays user stats from the existing analytics service."]
  
  WHY:
  [The engineering reason — what problem does this solve, or what
   capability does it add? One sentence.]
  
  ACCEPTANCE CONDITIONS:
  [Rewritten in engineering terms, not QA terms.
   Each condition must be verifiable by looking at code or running a test.
   
   BAD: "User can see their profile"
   GOOD: "GET /api/users/:id returns a 200 with { id, name, email, 
          createdAt } shape. If the user does not exist, returns 404 
          with { error: 'User not found' }."
  ]
  
  OUT OF SCOPE FOR THIS TASK:
  [Explicit list of related things this task does NOT include.
   This prevents the implementer from going wide.]
  
  DEPENDS ON: [T-00X or "none"]
  MUST PRECEDE: [T-00X or "none"]
  
  ESTIMATED SIZE: trivial | small | medium | large
  RISK LEVEL: low | medium | high
  RISK REASON: [why — only fill if medium or high]
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

════════════════════════════════════════
STEP 4 — EXECUTION PLAN
════════════════════════════════════════
Now sequence the normalized tasks.

4a. DEPENDENCY GRAPH
Build the dependency chain. Show which tasks must complete before others can start.
Format as a simple ordered list with indentation showing dependency:

  T-001 (no dependencies)
  T-002 (no dependencies)
    └── T-004 (depends on T-002)
    └── T-005 (depends on T-002)
        └── T-007 (depends on T-005)
  T-003 (no dependencies)
    └── T-006 (depends on T-003)

4b. PARALLEL BATCHES
Group tasks into batches that can run in parallel (tasks with no
dependency between them). A coding agent can execute one batch at a time.

  BATCH 1 — run first (no dependencies):
    T-001: [title]
    T-002: [title]
    T-003: [title]

  BATCH 2 — run after Batch 1 completes:
    T-004: [title] (was blocked by T-002)
    T-005: [title] (was blocked by T-002)
    T-006: [title] (was blocked by T-003)

  BATCH 3 — run after Batch 2 completes:
    T-007: [title]

4c. RISK SEQUENCING NOTE
If any HIGH risk tasks exist, flag whether they should be done first
(to fail fast) or last (to avoid destabilizing early work).
Recommend explicitly.

